Plotting Distributions

Gabriel Odom

8/30/2018

Random variables in R are shown on https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/stats/html/Distributions.html

There are two functions we will use: hist() and plot(density()). There is another function, summary() which will give us the mean and 5-number summary of a numeric vector.

Continuous Random Variables

The Normal Distribution

Sample Size of 10000

# Draw Random Sample: sqrt(5) ~= 2.24
xFullN <- rnorm(10000, mean = 2, sd = sqrt(5))

# Histogram
hist(xFullN)

# Summary
summary(xFullN)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -6.5902  0.4588  2.0167  2.0023  3.5290 10.3361
var(xFullN)
## [1] 5.041282
# Density Plots
density(xFullN)
## 
## Call:
##  density.default(x = xFullN)
## 
## Data: xFullN (10000 obs.);   Bandwidth 'bw' = 0.3203
## 
##        x                y            
##  Min.   :-7.551   Min.   :1.460e-06  
##  1st Qu.:-2.839   1st Qu.:1.627e-03  
##  Median : 1.873   Median :1.976e-02  
##  Mean   : 1.873   Mean   :5.300e-02  
##  3rd Qu.: 6.585   3rd Qu.:1.051e-01  
##  Max.   :11.297   Max.   :1.749e-01
plot(density(xFullN))

# Scatterplots
plot(xFullN)

Sample Size of 5

The Student’s \(t\) Distribution

Sample Size of 10000

# Draw Random Sample: sqrt(5) ~= 2.24
xFullSt <- rt(n = 10000, df = 4)

# Histogram
hist(xFullSt)

# Summary
summary(xFullSt)
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## -14.05062  -0.72624   0.01572   0.03056   0.77138  15.31834
var(xFullSt)
## [1] 2.04605
# Density Plots
plot(density(xFullSt))

# Scatterplot
plot(xFullSt)
